@mkleehammer  PyUnicode_GetLength won't work either, because (at least for SQL Server, and other DBMSs which use UTF-16 wvarchar) the driver is expecting the number of UTF-16 _code units_ and not _code points_ (which is equivalent to UTF-32 code units).

> Another open issue is that pyodbc is sending exact string lengths (ignore this bug for now) and causing SQL Server to cache a new plan for each execute of the same SQL with different string parameters. Would solving that issue automatically fix this one?

If "solving that issue" means binding parameters with the column size given to it by the server from SQLDescribeParam/Col/otherwise, then *yes*. E.g. an nvarchar(300) will result in binding a column size of 300. My PR which adds setinputsizes() will also fix this if the user sets the size to a suitable value for the column.

