You don't need `DjangoConnectionField`, you may use `relay.ConnectionField` instead 
```python
from graphene import relay

class AssetUnion(graphene.types.Union):
    class Meta:
        types = [FileAssetNode, QuestionAssetNode]

class AssetConnection(relay.Connection):
    class Meta:
        node = AssetUnion

class ParentNode(graphene.ObjectType):
    assets = relay.connectionField(AssetConnection)

    def resolve_assets(self, args, context, info):
        return chain(self.fileasset_set.all(), self.questionasset_set.all())
```

You may need to provide `resolve_type` method on `AssetUnion`, something like

```python
class AssetUnion(graphene.types.Union):
    class Meta:
        types = [FileAssetNode, QuestionAssetNode]

    @classmethod
    def resolve_type(cls, instance, context, info):
        if is_file_asset_node(instance):
            return FileAssetNode
        elif is_question_asset_node(instance):
            return QuestionAssetNode
        raise Exception()
```

@abtink I've found it to be a fairly common use case for me as a developer to want to rebuild with a higher log level without touching any of the actual source files.  The log level remains in the purview of `openthread-core-config.h` when `--with-log-level` is not passed.  Also, the developer may forcibly hard-code their desired log level in a platform-specific `openthread-core-config.h` without ifndef if they so choose.  

Similar to the introduction of otGetDynamicLogLevel, I think this PR makes the logging facility more configurable and convenient to use with minimal downside risks.  I would argue there is far more to get confused by in the logging design than whether this config option or the header is making the final log-level decision in the build.  

Any others that support this PR?

